## What is Pweb?
Pweb are web HTML5&nbsp;interactive pages. They are presented in a web page, as mini-sites, and contain custom variable data about the recipient. The variable data are used to show the recipient details about its particular situation and can be shown in rich graphical form, like charts and tables. The user can interact with the page filter and drill-down the data in order to self-analyze the data. For instance, there could be a Pweb displaying mobile usage, giving details about the cost on a monthly basis over a time span of 6 months.

## Why use HTML5 for Doxee's new Communication Technology
HTML stands for Hyper Text Mark-up Language. HTML5 is a revised version of the original HTML standard created in 1990 by the World Wide Web Consortium to define an Open Web Platform.&nbsp;HTML is a language used for structuring and presenting content on the Web consistently, across web browsers. HTML5 is the evolution of that standard to meet the increasing demands presented by todays rich media, cross device and mobile internet access requirements. As such, it is a great candidate for cross-platform mobile application development, as many of its features have been adapted with the consideration of running on low powered devices, such as smartphones and tablets and providing web developers with tools like CSS3. Importantly whilst running within a web browser, (as HTML5 does) it is not tied to the underlying operating system, freeing applications from the significant development and support overhead of multiple native applications (e.g. iOS, Android, BlackBerry etc.).

Using HTML5 provides advantages to businesses that develop and deploy web content and web applications, to create refined and accurate web pages and web systems that operate across devices, operating systems and web browsers. Write once, run anywhere. The plethora of devices, operating systems and screen sizes present numerous design, functional and layout considerations and problems if standards are not adhered to.

HTML5 will allow Doxee to offer the client new distribution channels to reach the end user and a wider span of strategies, which insist heavily on interactivity and user responses.

This choice will be disruptive for Doxee, which is an established CCM company, known for large production of one-way communication formats such as PDFs. With HTML5, Doxee is also able to connect the client to the end user via mobile devices, allowing the end user to interact with the communication and the client to have simple, fast feedback.

Here is the list of technical advantages of HTML5&nbsp;versus PDF in delivering interactive communications:

- No installation required

- Closer to native application, all mobile device features can be used easily

- Better interoperability: third-party open-source SDKs can be used as business accelerators for cost savings

- Faster, thanks to native browsers Javascript engine

- Cheaper to develop (open-community is expanding continuously)

- Custom code can be used for unlimited feature development

- Multiscreen / cross-device / mobile-ready / best coverage in the Mobile B2C world

- Investments on the big player&nbsp;[http://mobilehtml5.org/](http://mobilehtml5.org/)

- SEO friendly

## Pweb Authoring Tools
Pweb is produced with standard web HTML5 technology, leveraging JavaScript libraries and CSS. It is also possible to include in the Pweb advanced front-end JavaScript libraries such as Angular or React for navigation and interactivity, and other libraries to add more interactivity such as chart libraries.

Also, Pweb is produced either as a standalone file, meaning that the recipient can open and interact with Pweb offline because all its dependencies are embedded, or a pURL provided website that the user can open via web and devices with an internet connection.

 Doxee suggests the following components to be considered before starting the development of a Pweb. 

### HTML5 suggested open-source tools
As tools, it is possible to use any HTML5 editing tool. Below is a list of options:

- NotePad++

- Sublime Text&nbsp;

- Atom

- TextMate

- Adobe Dreamweaver

Only Adobe Dreamweaver allows a WYSIWYG interface.

Since there is no specific authoring tool, Pweb should be developed by suppliers that are professional in developing front-end contents.

> Note

Since professionals are involved in developing front-end technology, the use of node.js as a platform to generate the end result is recommended. There is no server work involved in the end product to generate, compile and compress the final Pweb.

### Accelerators
Accelerators are frameworks that assist the developer to write code that is compatible with any browser and device. Thanks to these libraries, the end result will be the same graphically and it will work on all browsers. Below a list of suggested accelerators:

- Twitter Bootstrap

- Vanilla by Ubuntu

- *Modulr.css*

- UIKit

It is also possible not to start the development from scratch and start working with front-end templates. These templates can also be bought from many stores on the internet, for example the Envato store ([market.envato.com](http://market.envato.com/)).

One of the templates that has been successfully used is AdminLTE ([almsaeedstudio.com/AdminLTE](http://almsaeedstudio.com/AdminLTE)). This template is already mobile responsive and behaves correctly with any browser window dimension. Below is an example of this tool.

## Pweb and the Doxee Platform
## pURL delivery
Personalized URL (pURL) is the channel through which Pvideo and Pweb are delivered.

pURLs can be of two different types:&nbsp;

- **Direct**: Permalink bound directly to the final users document and directly served from the Doxee Platform.

- **Indirect**: The end user can request access of a pURL from the Doxee Client portal. The client will first send a request which includes an XML with metadata (or indexes) regarding the requested document. Then, as a response, the client receives a JSON object in which there is a URL. By calling that URL, the client can receive the requested document. Upon downloading the document, the URL used for the last step gets reset. The user cannot use the last URL twice. In order to set up this kind of pURL, activities from Doxee client are needed.

A pURL can be delivered through the following channels:

Once the end user clicks on a pURL, the document, which can be a Pvideo, Pweb or other type, is served back directly to the user.

Even in the indirect pURL case, once the request is made by the client, there is no need for an on-demand application to serve the content back. There is another, much lighter technology that takes care of serving the document to the end user, without the need of an on-demand application.

> Note

At the moment, an external service must be used to connect the SMS Gateway to the Doxee Platform. Italy is the only country in which the SMS Gateway comes by default with the Doxee Platform.

## Doxee client integration
As shown in the image above, if delivery has to be made via indirect pURL, an integration by the client is needed. For example, the client will have to integrate, into their own web portal, a system that will call Doxees API to generate the indirect pURL, receive the response and show the user a link to click on, or open a new tab window with the temporary pURL.

## Monitoring model
In order to monitor the production of Pweb and Pvideo, the Doxee Platform produces standard Tracking &amp; Reporting events such as production, transfer and delivery.

In order to monitor display and reception, the event that gets triggered is bound to the pURL. This event is named "Personalized URL Download", code 1920, and is triggered when the pURL request is sent and the Doxee Platform receives it. For example, a user clicks on a link containing his/her pURL making a request, the Doxee Platform receives the request, looks for the payload to return and therefore triggers the response event.

Despite being a permanent or disposable pURL, the event is of user response type, and takes care of monitoring whether the document was successfully delivered or not to the requestor. Moreover, the event carries more data such as the download start time, download end time, and metadata about the document ID and the document class that it belongs to.

## Recommendations for Pweb authoring
> Important

In case of a standalone Pweb, extremely large sized assets should be avoided. Instead it is preferable to use SVG images which can be generated by JavaScript code.

> Important

It is recommended to avoid using any media file type such as videos (.mp4, .avi, etc.) or audio (.mp3) when developing a standalone Pweb because the size will increase considerably.
